wtWebCount6InputCounterClear.name: wtWebCount6InputCounterClear
wtWebCount6InputCounterClear.description: Clears the input counter after returning its value.

wtWebCount6InputValue.name: wtWebCount6InputValue
wtWebCount6InputValue.description: This variable is used to read the inputs of the digital I/O port. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebCount6SessCntrlPassword.name: wtWebCount6SessCntrlPassword
wtWebCount6SessCntrlPassword.description: Entering this password opens a session which is ended by writing a 1 to wtWebCount6SessCntrlLogout. When read this variable provides a string of length zero.

wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigMode.name: wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigMode
wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigMode.description: When the device is in SNMP configuration mode, the value 1 is returned, otherwise 0. If the read value is 0 even though the password was written, the device is already in config mode and the variables can only be read.

wtWebCount6SessCntrlLogout.name: wtWebCount6SessCntrlLogout
wtWebCount6SessCntrlLogout.description: If the device is in configuration mode and the session was opened by this SNMP Manager, writing a 1 to this variable will end the session and all parameters are stored. Writing a 2 discards all entries again. When read this variable provides the value 0.

wtWebCount6SessCntrlAdminPassword.name: wtWebCount6SessCntrlAdminPassword
wtWebCount6SessCntrlAdminPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with administrator rights. It can only be changed by the administrator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public.

wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigPassword.name: wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigPassword
wtWebCount6SessCntrlConfigPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with configurator rights. It can be changed by the administrator and by the configurator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public. When read this variable provides a null-pointer.

wtWebCount6MailAuthentication.description: Selection of the authentication modi: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. Bit 1 decided wether the community string of read operations is compared with the system password or not: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : SNMP enable

wtWebCount6SnmpSystemTrapEnable.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: ColdStart Bit 1: WarmStart Bit 2: Diag messages Bit 3-7: unused

wtWebCount6UdpAdminPort.name: wtWebCount6UdpAdminPort
wtWebCount6UdpAdminPort.description: Udp port to which the Udp queries ( short form GET requests) can be sent. This port number must be unique within the device.

wtWebCount6UdpEnable.name: wtWebCount6UdpEnable
wtWebCount6UdpEnable.description: Set this bit to enable UDP support: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : UDP enable

wtWebCount6UdpRemotePort.name: wtWebCount6UdpRemotePort
wtWebCount6UdpRemotePort.description: Udp remote port setting. If this value is set to zero, the source port read from a request will be used as destination port for the answer. A non zero value forced the destination port to this value.

wtWebCount6SyslogServerIP.name: wtWebCount6SyslogServerIP
wtWebCount6SyslogServerIP.description: Name or IP address of the Syslog server, which accepts the Syslog messgaes.

wtWebCount6SyslogServerPort.name: wtWebCount6SyslogServerPort
wtWebCount6SyslogServerPort.description: Portnumber of the Syslog servers, default 514.

wtWebCount6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable.name: wtWebCount6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable
wtWebCount6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: ColdStart Bit 1: WarmStart Bit 2: Diag Messages Bit 3-7: unused

wtWebCount6SyslogEnable.name: wtWebCount6SyslogEnable
wtWebCount6SyslogEnable.description: Set bit 0to enable Syslog: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Syslog enable

wtWebCount6FTPServerIP.name: wtWebCount6FTPServerIP
wtWebCount6FTPServerIP.description: Name or IP address of the FTP server, which accepts the FTP messages.

wtWebCount6FTPServerControlPort.name: wtWebCount6FTPServerControlPort
wtWebCount6FTPServerControlPort.description: Portnumber of the control port of the FTP server, default 21.

wtWebCount6FTPOption.name: wtWebCount6FTPOption
wtWebCount6FTPOption.description: Bit 0 switches the FTP Server in Passiv-Mode, the Client controls the data connection on its own: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : PASV enable

wtWebCount6FTPEnable.name: wtWebCount6FTPEnable
wtWebCount6FTPEnable.description: Set Bit 0 to enable FTP: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : FTP enable

wtWebCount6ReportTable.name: wtWebCount6ReportTable
wtWebCount6ReportTable.description: List of settings depending on the Report number.

wtWebCount6ReportEntry.name: wtWebCount6ReportEntry
wtWebCount6ReportEntry.description: Report parameters of the individual Reports.

wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger.name: wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger
wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger.description: This variable allows setting of individual input trigger conditions. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first four OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the inputs are to be considered (corresponding bit = 1) and which inputs are to ignore (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Mask for digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the inputs should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8, Bit 0-5: Level of digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 9-12 contain the counter bit (1=ON, 0=OFF). Inputs masked with the counter bit trigger an Report when the corresponding counter reaching the wtWebCount6ReportMaxCounterValue. Settings in OCTET 5-9 are then unused: OCTET 9 : unused OCTET 10: unused OCTET 11: unused OCTET 12, Bit 0-5: Counter bits of digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused.

wtWebCount6ReportSystemTrigger.name: wtWebCount6ReportSystemTrigger
wtWebCount6ReportSystemTrigger.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 7 : Timer OFF Bit 6 : Time Window Bit 5 : unused Bit 4 : unused Bit 3 : unused Bit 2 : unused Bit 1 : Timer Bit 0 : unused

wtWebCount6ReportMaxCounterValue.name: wtWebCount6ReportMaxCounterValue
wtWebCount6ReportMaxCounterValue.description: This variable configures a max. counter value. If an input counter value exceeds this max. value, the corresponding Report is triggered. Input counters with its mask bit unset in wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger are not considered.

wtWebCount6ReportEnable.name: wtWebCount6ReportEnable
wtWebCount6ReportEnable.description: Binary coded Report enable: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: Output Switch Enable Bit 1: Mail Enable Bit 2: SNMP Trap enable Bit 3: UDP enable Bit 4: unused Bit 5: TCP Client enable Bit 6: Syslog Messages enable Bit 7: FTP Client enable

wtWebCount6ReportMailAddr.name: wtWebCount6ReportMailAddr
wtWebCount6ReportMailAddr.description: E-Mail address for sending the Report mail to.

wtWebCount6ReportMailText.name: wtWebCount6ReportMailText
wtWebCount6ReportMailText.description: Report mail text: States of the Webio device can be included by using special tags. Please refer to the respective Webio manual

wtWebCount6ReportSnmpManagerIP.name: wtWebCount6ReportSnmpManagerIP
wtWebCount6ReportSnmpManagerIP.description: IP address of the SNMP Manager to which the Webio device should send SNMP traps.

wtWebCount6ReportSnmpTrapText.name: wtWebCount6ReportSnmpTrapText
wtWebCount6ReportSnmpTrapText.description: This text appears in the trap body.

wtWebCount6ReportUdpIpAddr.name: wtWebCount6ReportUdpIpAddr
wtWebCount6ReportUdpIpAddr.description: IP address of the UDP listener to which the Webio device should send UDP traps.

wtWebCount6ReportUdpPort.name: wtWebCount6ReportUdpPort
wtWebCount6ReportUdpPort.description: Port number of the UDP listener to which the Webio device should send UDP traps.

wtWebCount6ReportUdpText.name: wtWebCount6ReportUdpText
wtWebCount6ReportUdpText.description: This text appears in the UDP trap body.

wtWebCount6ReportTcpIpAddr.name: wtWebCount6ReportTcpIpAddr
wtWebCount6ReportTcpIpAddr.description: IP address of the TCP listener to which the Webio device should send TCP traps.

wtWebCount6ReportTcpPort.name: wtWebCount6ReportTcpPort
wtWebCount6ReportTcpPort.description: Port number of the TCP listener to which the Webio device should send TCP traps.

wtWebCount6ReportTcpText.name: wtWebCount6ReportTcpText
wtWebCount6ReportTcpText.description: This text appears in the TCP trap body.

wtWebCount6ReportSyslogIpAddr.name: wtWebCount6ReportSyslogIpAddr
wtWebCount6ReportSyslogIpAddr.description: IP address of the syslog server to which the Webio device should send syslog messages.

wtWebCount6ReportSyslogPort.name: wtWebCount6ReportSyslogPort
wtWebCount6ReportSyslogPort.description: Port number of the syslog server to which the Webio device should send syslog messages.

wtWebCount6ReportSyslogText.name: wtWebCount6ReportSyslogText
wtWebCount6ReportSyslogText.description: Every message starts with the priority key, a time stamp and the host ip address, according RFC3164. This text appears in the following syslog message body.

wtWebCount6ReportFtpDataPort.name: wtWebCount6ReportFtpDataPort
wtWebCount6ReportFtpDataPort.description: Local data port: 1..65535 or AUTO: the next free port will be assigned.

wtWebCount6ReportFtpFileName.name: wtWebCount6ReportFtpFileName
wtWebCount6ReportFtpFileName.description: Name of the file including path informations.

wtWebCount6ReportFtpText.name: wtWebCount6ReportFtpText
wtWebCount6ReportFtpText.description: Message text to store on the FTP server.

wtWebCount6ReportFtpOption.name: wtWebCount6ReportFtpOption
wtWebCount6ReportFtpOption.description: Binary coded options, select only one option at the same time: STORE = replace file APPEND = append message at the end of the file Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0 : STORE Bit 1 : APPEND Bit 2-7: unused

wtWebCount6ReportTimerCron.name: wtWebCount6ReportTimerCron
wtWebCount6ReportTimerCron.description: This entry contains 5 space or tab seperated text fields for time trigger definition. Each field must match with the actual time to trigger a report, weekday and day of month are interpreted separatley. 1: Minutes Range 0-59 2. Hours Range 0-23, 0 is midnight 3: Day of month Range 1-31 4: Month Range 1-12 5: Weekday Range 0-6, 0 is sunday Syntax for every field: - an asterix (*) enables every possible setting of a field - single numbers seperated by commas - a partition within the allowed range (1-5) - step size within an partition of the allowed range (0-59/2: every second minute).

wtWebCount6ReportGlobalEnable.name: wtWebCount6ReportGlobalEnable
wtWebCount6ReportGlobalEnable.description: Binary coded Report activation: Die OCTETS werden bitweise interpretiert. Bit 0 entspricht dem LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Report enable

wtWebCount6ReportCounterClear.name: wtWebCount6ReportCounterClear
wtWebCount6ReportCounterClear.description: Binary coded options: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Counter clear on Report send

wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange.name: wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange
wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange.description: This variable configures a max. counter value within a time slot. If an input counter value exceeds this max. value, the corresponding Report is triggered. Input counters with its mask bit unset in wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger are not considered. A value of Zero disable the tracing of rate of change.

wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeWindow.name: wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeWindow
wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeWindow.description: This variable configures the time slot of wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange. Input counters with its mask bit unset in wtWebCount6ReportInputTrigger are not considered. A value of Zero disable the tracing of rate of change.

wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeMode.name: wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeMode
wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChangeMode.description: Binary coded options: Minimum mode: a report will be send if the count of pulses is lower than the given pulse count in wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange. Maximum mode: a report will be send if the count of pulses is greater than the pulse count given in wtWebCount6ReportRateOfChange. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, use only one bit at a time. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 1-7: unused Bit 2 : Maximum Mode Bit 1 : Minimum Mode Bit 0 : Rate of Change OFF

wtWebCount6InputPortTable.name: wtWebCount6InputPortTable
wtWebCount6InputPortTable.description: List of settings depending on the input number.

wtWebCount6InputPortEntry.name: wtWebCount6InputPortEntry
wtWebCount6InputPortEntry.description: Input parameter for the individual inputs.

wtWebCount6PortInputMode.name: wtWebCount6PortInputMode
wtWebCount6PortInputMode.description: Binary coded modes: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. Selection for input 0-1: OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 4-7: unused Bit 3 : Bidirectional counter enable Bit 2 : unused Bit 1 : Change detection enable Bit 0 : unused

wtWebCount6PortInputFilter.name: wtWebCount6PortInputFilter
wtWebCount6PortInputFilter.description: Pulses with a duration shorter than here specified (duration in 1/1000 sec), are ignored.

wtWebCount6PortInputPulsePolarity.name: wtWebCount6PortInputPulsePolarity
wtWebCount6PortInputPulsePolarity.description: This value defines the polarity of the input pulse. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0 : negative polarity Bit 1 : positive polarity Bit 2-7 : unused

wtWebCount6PortInputBicountInactivTimeou.name: wtWebCount6PortInputBicountInactivTimeout
wtWebCount6PortInputBicountInactivTimeou.description: Pulse chains with a duration shorter than here specified (in 1/10 sek), are ignored.

wtWebCount6PortInputCounterSet.name: wtWebCount6PortInputCounterSet
wtWebCount6PortInputCounterSet.description: Writing to this variable presets the counter, while reading returns the actual value.

wtWebCount6DiagErrorCount.name: wtWebCount6DiagErrorCount
wtWebCount6DiagErrorCount.description: Number of entries in the error memory.

wtWebCount6DiagErrorIndex.name: wtWebCount6DiagErrorIndex
wtWebCount6DiagErrorIndex.description: The value of this variable is used as an index to read an error massege from wtWebCount6DiagErrorMessage. Errors are numbered from 1 to wtWebCount6DiagErrorCount. Writing a valid value into this variable, making the appropriate message readable from wtWebCount6DiagErrorMessage.

wtWebCount6DiagErrorMessage.name: wtWebCount6DiagErrorMessage
wtWebCount6DiagErrorMessage.description: Using wtWebCount6DiagErrorIndex as an index, the appropriate message is available.

wtWebCount6DiagErrorClear.name: wtWebCount6DiagErrorClear
wtWebCount6DiagErrorClear.description: Writing 1 into this variable clears all diagnosis messages.

wtWebCount6Alert1.name: wtWebCount6Alert1
wtWebCount6Alert1.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 1 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert2.name: wtWebCount6Alert2
wtWebCount6Alert2.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 2 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert3.name: wtWebCount6Alert3
wtWebCount6Alert3.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 3 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert4.name: wtWebCount6Alert4
wtWebCount6Alert4.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 4 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert5.name: wtWebCount6Alert5
wtWebCount6Alert5.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 5 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert6.name: wtWebCount6Alert6
wtWebCount6Alert6.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 6 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert7.name: wtWebCount6Alert7
wtWebCount6Alert7.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 7 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert8.name: wtWebCount6Alert8
wtWebCount6Alert8.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 8 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert9.name: wtWebCount6Alert9
wtWebCount6Alert9.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 9 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert10.name: wtWebCount6Alert10
wtWebCount6Alert10.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 10 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert11.name: wtWebCount6Alert11
wtWebCount6Alert11.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 11 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6Alert12.name: wtWebCount6Alert12
wtWebCount6Alert12.description: This SNMP trap is generated when Report 12 was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebCount6AlertDiag.name: wtWebCount6AlertDiag
wtWebCount6AlertDiag.description: This SNMP trap is generated when a diagnosis/error message was triggered, SNMP trap enable is set and SNMP is enabled.

wtWebioEA6x6InputCounterClear.name: wtWebioEA6x6InputCounterClear
wtWebioEA6x6InputCounterClear.description: Clears the input counter after returning its value.

wtWebioEA6x6InputState.name: wtWebioEA6x6InputState
wtWebioEA6x6InputState.description: Value of a single input bit.

wtWebioEA6x6InputValue.name: wtWebioEA6x6InputValue
wtWebioEA6x6InputValue.description: This variable is used to read the inputs of the digital I/O port. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3, unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6OutputState.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputState
wtWebioEA6x6OutputState.description: Value of a single output bit.

wtWebioEA6x6OutputValue.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputValue
wtWebioEA6x6OutputValue.description: This variable is used to read and write the outputs of the digital I/O port. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3, unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6SetOutput.name: wtWebioEA6x6SetOutput
wtWebioEA6x6SetOutput.description: This variable allows setting of individual digital outputs. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first two OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the outputs are to be set (corresponding bit = 1) and which outputs are to remain unchanged (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3 : unused OCTET 4 : Bit 0-5: Mask for digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the inputs should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8 : Bit 0-5: Level of digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlPassword.name: wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlPassword
wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlPassword.description: Entering this password opens a session which is ended by writing a 1 to wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlLogout. When read this variable provides a string of length zero.

wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigMode
wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigMode.description: When the device is in SNMP configuration mode, the value 1 is returned, otherwise 0. If the read value is 0 even though the password was written, the device is already in config mode and the variables can only be read.

wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlLogout.name: wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlLogout
wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlLogout.description: If the device is in configuration mode and the session was opened by this SNMP Manager, writing a 1 to this variable will end the session and all parameters are stored. Writing a 2 discards all entries again. When read this variable provides the value 0.

wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlAdminPassword.name: wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlAdminPassword
wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlAdminPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with administrator rights. It can only be changed by the administrator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public.

wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigPassword.name: wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigPassword
wtWebioEA6x6SessCntrlConfigPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with configurator rights. It can be changed by the administrator and by the configurator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public. When read this variable provides a null-pointer.

wtWebioEA6x6DeviceName.name: wtWebioEA6x6DeviceName
wtWebioEA6x6DeviceName.description: Name of the Webio, which is user definable.

wtWebioEA6x6DeviceText.name: wtWebioEA6x6DeviceText
wtWebioEA6x6DeviceText.description: Description of the Webio, which is user definable.

wtWebioEA6x6DeviceLocation.name: wtWebioEA6x6DeviceLocation
wtWebioEA6x6DeviceLocation.description: Description of the location of the Webio, which is user definable.

wtWebioEA6x6DeviceContact.name: wtWebioEA6x6DeviceContact
wtWebioEA6x6DeviceContact.description: Contact address of the system operator of the Webio, which is user definable.

wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetHrs.name: wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetHrs
wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetHrs.description: Offset hours for the time zone (winter time) with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetMin.name: wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetMin
wtWebioEA6x6TzOffsetMin.description: Offset minutes for the time zone (winter time) with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6TzEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6TzEnable
wtWebioEA6x6TzEnable.description: Binary coded conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Apply Timezone

wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetHrs.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetHrs
wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetHrs.description: Offset hours of the time zone (summer time) with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetMin.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetMin
wtWebioEA6x6StTzOffsetMin.description: Offset minutes of the time zone (summer time) with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzEnable
wtWebioEA6x6StTzEnable.description: Binary coded conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Apply Summertime

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMonth.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMonth
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMonth.description: Month in which the change is made from winter time to summer time.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMode
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMode.description: Mode of the day of the week for which the change is made from winter time to summer time.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartWday.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartWday
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartWday.description: Day of the week on which the change is made from winter time to summer time

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartHrs.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartHrs
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartHrs.description: Hour in which the time zone is changed from winter to summer time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMin.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMin
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStartMin.description: Minute in which the time zone is changed from winter to summer time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMonth.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMonth
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMonth.description: Month in which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMode
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMode.description: Mode of the week day on which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopWday.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopWday
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopWday.description: Day of the week on which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopHrs.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopHrs
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopHrs.description: Hour at which the time zone is changed from summer to winter time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMin.name: wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMin
wtWebioEA6x6StTzStopMin.description: Minute at which the time zone is changed from summer to winter time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer1.name: wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer1
wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer1.description: IP address or name of the 1st time server in ASCII

wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer2.name: wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer2
wtWebioEA6x6TimeServer2.description: IP address or name of the 2nd time server in ASCII

wtWebioEA6x6TsEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6TsEnable
wtWebioEA6x6TsEnable.description: Binary coded conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Apply Time Server

wtWebioEA6x6TsSyncTime.name: wtWebioEA6x6TsSyncTime
wtWebioEA6x6TsSyncTime.description: Daily synchronisation time with the time server (hour: 0-23).

wtWebioEA6x6ClockHrs.name: wtWebioEA6x6ClockHrs
wtWebioEA6x6ClockHrs.description: Clock hours taking into account the time zone settings.

wtWebioEA6x6ClockMin.name: wtWebioEA6x6ClockMin
wtWebioEA6x6ClockMin.description: Clock minutes taking into account the time zone settings.

wtWebioEA6x6ClockDay.name: wtWebioEA6x6ClockDay
wtWebioEA6x6ClockDay.description: Date: Day of the month, taking into account the time zone settings.

wtWebioEA6x6ClockMonth.name: wtWebioEA6x6ClockMonth
wtWebioEA6x6ClockMonth.description: Date: Month, taking into account the time zone settings.

wtWebioEA6x6ClockYear.name: wtWebioEA6x6ClockYear
wtWebioEA6x6ClockYear.description: Date: Year, taking into account the time zone settings.

wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer1.name: wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer1
wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer1.description: IP address of the 1st DNS server in ASCII

wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer2.name: wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer2
wtWebioEA6x6DnsServer2.description: IP address of the 2nd DNS server in ASCII

wtWebioEA6x6AddConfig.name: wtWebioEA6x6AddConfig
wtWebioEA6x6AddConfig.description: Additional configuration (1=ON): Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1: DHCP enable Bit 0: BOOTP enable

wtWebioEA6x6Startup.name: wtWebioEA6x6Startup
wtWebioEA6x6Startup.description: Binary coded start page, more than one page must not be selected: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 2: user.htm Bit 1: home.htm Bit 0: index.htm

wtWebioEA6x6GetHeaderEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6GetHeaderEnable
wtWebioEA6x6GetHeaderEnable.description: If bits are set, every answer of a short form GET question will be lead by the IP-address and name of the device (Header) or a HTTP header (HTTP): Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 2-7: unused Bit 1 : GET HTTP enable Bit 0 : GET Header enable

wtWebioEA6x6HttpInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6HttpInputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6HttpInputTrigger.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6HttpPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6HttpPort
wtWebioEA6x6HttpPort.description: Definition of the standard HTML port (Default: 80).

wtWebioEA6x6MailReply.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailReply
wtWebioEA6x6MailReply.description: Reply address for the mail server.

wtWebioEA6x6MailServer.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailServer
wtWebioEA6x6MailServer.description: Name or IP address of the mail server.

wtWebioEA6x6MailEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailEnable
wtWebioEA6x6MailEnable.description: Set this bit to enable the sending of mails: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Mail enable

wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthentication.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthentication
wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthentication.description: Selection of the authentication modi: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : POP3 before SMTP Bit 1 : ESMTP, authentication Bit 0 : SMTP, no authentication

wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthUser.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthUser
wtWebioEA6x6MailAuthUser.description: Name of the user to be authenticated.

wtWebioEA6x6MailPop3Server.name: wtWebioEA6x6MailPop3Server
wtWebioEA6x6MailPop3Server.description: Name or Ip-address of the POP3 Servers.

wtWebioEA6x6SnmpEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6SnmpEnable
wtWebioEA6x6SnmpEnable.description: Set bit 0 to enable SNMP. If disabled, the device did not respond to any SNMP requests. Bit 1 decided wether the community string of read operations is compared with the system password or not: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : SNMP enable

wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapManagerIP.name: wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapManagerIP
wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapManagerIP.description: Name or IP address of the TCP server which accepts the system trap.

wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapEnable
wtWebioEA6x6SnmpSystemTrapEnable.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: ColdStart Bit 1: WarmStart Bit 2: Diag messages Bit 3-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6UdpAdminPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6UdpAdminPort
wtWebioEA6x6UdpAdminPort.description: Udp port to which the Udp queries ( short form GET requests) can be sent. This port number must be unique within the device.

wtWebioEA6x6UdpEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6UdpEnable
wtWebioEA6x6UdpEnable.description: Set this bit to enable UDP support: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : UDP enable

wtWebioEA6x6UdpRemotePort.name: wtWebioEA6x6UdpRemotePort
wtWebioEA6x6UdpRemotePort.description: Udp remote port setting. If this value is set to zero, the source port read from a request will be used as destination port for the answer. A non zero value forced the destination port to this value.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTable.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTable
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTable.description: Table of properties of the binary mode.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryOperationMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryOperationMode
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryOperationMode.description: Selection of the operation mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : UDP Peer Bit 1 : TCP Client Bit 0 : TCP Server

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerLocalPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerLocalPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerLocalPort.description: Local TCP port for data exchange in this server mode. This port number must be unique within the device. Reserved port number must not be used (refere to the manual).

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerInputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerInputTrigger.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerApplicationMo.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerApplicationMode
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerApplicationMo.description: Selection of the application mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 4-7: unused Bit 3 : OPC Device Bit 2 : Box2Box Slave Bit 1 : Compatible 50xxx Bit 0 : Default

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientLocalPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientLocalPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientLocalPort.description: Local TCP port for data exchange in this client mode. This port number must be unique within the device. Reserved port number must not be used (refere to the manual).

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPort.description: Port number of the server. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the server port to zero.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerIpAddr.description: Ip address of the server. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the server IP address to 0.0.0.0.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPasswor.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPassword
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerPasswor.description: Building a connection may be protected by the administrator password of the server. Enter the server password to establish the connection, if a server administrator password exists.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInactivity.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInactivity
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInactivity.description: Connection timeout in 100ms. If no data are exchanged within the specified time, the device closes the connection to the server. The value 0 deactivates the timer. Using the Box2Box mode this function is disabled.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInputTrigger.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInterval.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInterval
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientInterval.description: Configurable interval with a 100ms base, in which the Webio device sends data to the configured application. A interval of zero stopps the periodical sending.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientApplicationMo.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientApplicationMode
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientApplicationMo.description: Selection of the application mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : Box2Box Slave Bit 1 : Compatible 50xxx Bit 0 : Default

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerLocalPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerLocalPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerLocalPort.description: Local UDP port for data exchange in this peer to peer mode. This port number must be unique within the device. Reserved port number must not be used (refere to the manual).

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemotePort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemotePort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemotePort.description: Port number of the remote device. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the remote port to zero.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemoteIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemoteIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerRemoteIpAddr.description: Ip address of the remote device. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the remote device IP address to 0.0.0.0.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInputTrigger.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInterval.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInterval
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerInterval.description: Configurable interval with a 100ms base, in which the Webio device sends data to the configured remote device. A interval of zero stopps the periodical sending.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerApplicationMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerApplicationMode
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryUdpPeerApplicationMode.description: Selection of the application mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : Box2Box Slave Bit 1 : Compatible 50xxx Bit 0 : Default

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedPort.description: Port number of the remote device, after connection has been established. In case of no connection or missing port informations a zero will be read.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryConnectedIpAddr.description: IP address of the remote device, after connection has been established. In case of no connection or missing port informations 0.0.0.0 will be read.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerClientHttpPor.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerClientHttpPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpServerClientHttpPor.description: HTTP port number of the remote device at TCP Server Mode. If an mailfunction occurs status informations will be send to this port. Not used at mode Compatible 50xxx.

wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerHttpPor.name: wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerHttpPort
wtWebioEA6x6BinaryTcpClientServerHttpPor.description: HTTP port number of the remote device at TCP Client Mode. In the operating mode Box2Box connection status informations will be exchanged through this port.

wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerIP.name: wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerIP
wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerIP.description: Name or IP address of the Syslog server, which accepts the Syslog messgaes.

wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerPort
wtWebioEA6x6SyslogServerPort.description: Portnumber of the Syslog servers, default 514.

wtWebioEA6x6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable
wtWebioEA6x6SyslogSystemMessagesEnable.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: ColdStart Bit 1: WarmStart Bit 2: Diag Messages Bit 3-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6SyslogEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6SyslogEnable
wtWebioEA6x6SyslogEnable.description: Set bit 0to enable Syslog: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Syslog enable

wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerIP.name: wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerIP
wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerIP.description: Name or IP address of the FTP server, which accepts the FTP messages.

wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerControlPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerControlPort
wtWebioEA6x6FTPServerControlPort.description: Portnumber of the control port of the FTP server, default 21.

wtWebioEA6x6FTPOption.name: wtWebioEA6x6FTPOption
wtWebioEA6x6FTPOption.description: Bit 0 switches the FTP Server in Passiv-Mode, the Client controls the data connection on its own: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : PASV enable

wtWebioEA6x6FTPEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6FTPEnable
wtWebioEA6x6FTPEnable.description: Set Bit 0 to enable FTP: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : FTP enable

wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeTable.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeTable
wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeTable.description: Table of output mode configurations dependent on the output indices.

wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeEntry.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeEntry
wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeEntry.description: Output mode configurations of the individual outputs.

wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeBit.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeBit
wtWebioEA6x6OutputModeBit.description: This binary coded output mode defines the individual operation mode for any output. More than one mode must not be selected. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 6-7: unused Bit 5 : Logic Bit 4 : Binary 2 Bit 3 : Binary 1 Bit 2 : SNMP Bit 1 : UDP ASCII Bit 0 : HTTP

wtWebioEA6x6SafetyTimeout.name: wtWebioEA6x6SafetyTimeout
wtWebioEA6x6SafetyTimeout.description: After this period of time (multiple of 100ms) without receiving data outputs switch to their Safety States. For each output a independend safety state could be defined.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTable.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTable
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTable.description: List of settings depending on the alarm number.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEntry.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEntry
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEntry.description: Alarm parameters of the individual alarms.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmInputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmInputTrigger.description: This variable allows setting of individual input trigger conditions. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first four OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the inputs are to be considered (corresponding bit = 1) and which inputs are to ignore (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3 : unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Mask for digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the inputs should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8, Bit 0-5: Level of digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 9-12 contain the ANY bit (1=ON, 0=OFF). Inputs masked with the any bit trigger with any change of the corresponding input bit. Settings in OCTET 5-9 are then unused: OCTET 9 : unused OCTET 10: unused OCTET 11: unused OCTET 12, Bit 0-5: ANY bits of digital inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmOutputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmOutputTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmOutputTrigger.description: This variable allows setting of individual output trigger conditions. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first four OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the outputs are to be considered (corresponding bit = 1) and which outputs are to ignore (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3 : unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-5: Mask for digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the outputs should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8, Bit 0-5: Level of digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused OCTETS 9-12 contain the ANY bit (1=ON, 0=OFF). Outputs masked with the any bit trigger with any change of the corresponding output bit. Settings in OCTET 5-9 are then unused: OCTET 9 : unused OCTET 10: unused OCTET 11: unused OCTET 12, Bit 0-5: ANY bits of digital outputs 0-5 Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSystemTrigger.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSystemTrigger
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSystemTrigger.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 4-7: unused Bit 3 : Warm Start Bit 2 : Cold Start Bit 1 : Timer Bit 0 : Load Control

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMaxCounterValue.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMaxCounterValue
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMaxCounterValue.description: This variable configures a max. counter value. If an input counter value exceeds this max. value, the corresponding alarm is triggered. Input counters with its mask bit unset in wtWebioEA6x6AlarmInputTrigger are not considered.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEnable.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEnable
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmEnable.description: Binary coded alarm enable: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: Mail Enable Bit 1: SNMP Trap enable Bit 2: UDP enable Bit 3: Send inputs to pending TCP connections Bit 4: TCP Client enable Bit 5: Syslog Messages enable Bit 6-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailAddr
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailAddr.description: E-Mail address for sending the alarm mail to.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailText.description: Alarm mail text: States of the Webio device can be included by using special tags. Please refer to the respective Webio manual

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpManagerIP.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpManagerIP
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpManagerIP.description: IP address of the SNMP Manager to which the Webio device should send SNMP traps.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapText.description: This text appears in the trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpIpAddr.description: IP address of the UDP listener to which the Webio device should send UDP traps.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpPort
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpPort.description: Port number of the UDP listener to which the Webio device should send UDP traps.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpText.description: This text appears in the UDP trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpIpAddr.description: IP address of the TCP listener to which the Webio device should send TCP traps.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpPort
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpPort.description: Port number of the TCP listener to which the Webio device should send TCP traps.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpText.description: This text appears in the TCP trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogIpAddr.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogIpAddr
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogIpAddr.description: IP address of the syslog server to which the Webio device should send syslog messages.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogPort
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogPort.description: Port number of the syslog server to which the Webio device should send syslog messages.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogText.description: Every message starts with the priority key, a time stamp and the host ip address, according RFC3164. This text appears in the following syslog message body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpDataPort.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpDataPort
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpDataPort.description: Local data port: 1..65535 or AUTO: the next free port will be assigned.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpFileName.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpFileName
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpFileName.description: Name of the file including path informations.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpText.description: Message text to store on the FTP server.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpOption.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpOption
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpOption.description: Binary coded options, select only one option at the same time: STORE = replace file APPEND = append message at the end of the file Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0 : STORE Bit 1 : APPEND Bit 2-7: unused

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTimerCron.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTimerCron
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTimerCron.description: This entry contains 5 space or tab seperated text fields for time trigger definition. Each field must match with the actual time to trigger a message, weekday and day of month are interpreted separatley. 1: Minutes Range 0-59 2. Hours Range 0-23, 0 is midnight 3: Day of month Range 1-31 4: Month Range 1-12 5: Weekday Range 0-6, 0 is sunday Syntax for every field: - an asterix (*) enables every possible setting of a field - single numbers seperated by commas - a partition within the allowed range (1-5) - step size within an partition of the allowed range (0-59/2: every second minute).

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmMailReleaseText.description: Release Alarm mail text: States of the Webio device can be included by using special tags. Please refer to the respective Webio manual

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSnmpTrapReleaseText.description: This text appears in the trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmUdpReleaseText.description: This text appears in the UDP trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmTcpReleaseText.description: This text appears in the TCP trap body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmSyslogReleaseText.description: Every message starts with the priority key, a time stamp and the host ip address, according RFC3164. This text appears in the following syslog message body.

wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpReleaseText.name: wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpReleaseText
wtWebioEA6x6AlarmFtpReleaseText.description: Message text to store on the FTP server.

wtWebioEA6x6InputPortTable.name: wtWebioEA6x6InputPortTable
wtWebioEA6x6InputPortTable.description: List of settings depending on the input number.

wtWebioEA6x6InputPortEntry.name: wtWebioEA6x6InputPortEntry
wtWebioEA6x6InputPortEntry.description: Input parameter for the individual inputs.

wtWebioEA6x6PortInputMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortInputMode
wtWebioEA6x6PortInputMode.description: Binary coded modes: Selecting short pulse detection enable by setting the corresponding bit to 1 enables interrupt support for counting. Only positive edges are accepted as trigger source. The maximum counting frequenz equals 2000 Hz. This mode is available for inputs 0-3 only. Selecting counter clear on read by setting the corresponding bit to 1 enables the corresponding counter to be cleared automatically every time it is read, except HTTP reading with user rights. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each set of octets corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. Selection for input 0-3: OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : Counter clear on read Bit 1 : Change detection enable (default) Bit 0 : Short Pulse detection enable Selection for inputs 4-5: OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 2-7: unused Bit 1 : Counter clear on read Bit 0 : Change detection enable (default)

wtWebioEA6x6PortInputFilter.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortInputFilter
wtWebioEA6x6PortInputFilter.description: Pulses with a duration shorter than here specified (duration in 1/1000 sec), are ignored.

wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountPulsePolarit.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountPulsePolarity
wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountPulsePolarit.description: This value defines the polarity of the input pulse. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0 : negative polarity Bit 1 : positive polarity Bit 2-7 : unused

wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountInactivTimeo.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountInactivTimeout
wtWebioEA6x6PortInputBicountInactivTimeo.description: Pulse chains with a duration shorter than here specified (in 1/10 sek), are ignored.

wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortTable.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortTable
wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortTable.description: List of settings depending on the output number.

wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortEntry.name: wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortEntry
wtWebioEA6x6OutputPortEntry.description: Output parameters of the individual outputs.

wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputGroupMode.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputGroupMode
wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputGroupMode.description: It is possible to connect outputs together to increase the output current. This could be done by connecting 2 or 4 outputs in a group together. All bits of such a group has to be set all together in the same way. This variable configures this group scheme. If one output bit of a group is set, all other output bits of the same group will be set in the same manner. More than one configuration must not be selected. Selection for outputs 0-3: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0 : outputs 0,1,2,3 disconnected (default) Bit 1 : outputs 0+1, 2+3 connected Bit 2 : outputs 0+1+2+3 connected Bit 3-7 : unused Selection for outputs 4-7: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0 : outputs 4, 5 disconnected (default) Bit 1 : outputs 4+5 connected Bit 2-7 : unused Selection for outputs 8-11: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused OCTET 4: unused

wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputSafetyState.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputSafetyState
wtWebioEA6x6PortOutputSafetyState.description: This variable allows setting of individual digital outputs. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first four OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the outputs are to be set (corresponding bit = 1) and which outputs are to remain unchanged (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3 : unused OCTET 4, Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Mask for digital output OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the outputs to be changed should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8, Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Level of digital output

wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputMask.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputMask
wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputMask.description: Selecting one of these inputs by setting the corresponding bit to 1 enables the logic function for the output identified by the index within this table. The calculation take place in 4 steps: 1. Selecting inputs (wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputMask) 2. Inverting inputs if necessary (wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputInverter) 3. Logical combination (wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicFunction) 4. Inverting the result if necessary (wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicOutputInverter) OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0-5 : inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7 : unused

wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputInverter.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputInverter
wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicInputInverter.description: Every input bit selected here will be inverted. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0-5 : inputs 0-5 Bit 6-7 : unused

wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicOutputInverter.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortLogicOutputInverter

wtWebioEA6x6PortPulsePolarity.name: wtWebioEA6x6PortPulsePolarity

OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 0 : negative polarity Bit 1 : positive polarity Bit 2-7 : unused

wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputCounterClear.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputCounterClear
wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputCounterClear.description: Clears the input counter after returning its value.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputState.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputState
wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputState.description: Value of a single input bit.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputValue.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputValue
wtWebioEA2x2ERPInputValue.description: This variable is used to read the inputs of the digital I/O port. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-1: Digital outputs 0-1

wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputState.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputState
wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputState.description: Value of a single output bit.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputValue.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputValue
wtWebioEA2x2ERPOutputValue.description: This variable is used to read and write the outputs of the digital I/O port. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-1: Digital outputs 0-1 Bit 2-7: ungenutzt

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSetOutput.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSetOutput
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSetOutput.description: This variable allows setting of individual digital outputs. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an output. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. The first two OCTETS contain the mask which determines which of the outputs are to be set (corresponding bit = 1) and which outputs are to remain unchanged (corresponding bit = 0): OCTET 1 : unused OCTET 2 : unused OCTET 3 : unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-1: Mask for digital outputs 0-1 OCTETS 5-8 contain the level (1=HIGH, 0=LOW) which the outputs should assume: OCTET 5 : unused OCTET 6 : unused OCTET 7 : unused OCTET 8, Bit 0-1: Level of digital outputs 0-1

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlPassword.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlPassword
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlPassword.description: Entering this password opens a session which is ended by writing a 1 to wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlLogout. When read this variable provides a string of length zero.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigMode.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigMode
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigMode.description: When the device is in SNMP configuration mode, the value 1 is returned, otherwise 0. If the read value is 0 even though the password was written, the device is already in config mode and the variables can only be read.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlLogout.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlLogout
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlLogout.description: If the device is in configuration mode and the session was opened by this SNMP Manager, writing a 1 to this variable will end the session and all parameters are stored. Writing a 2 discards all entries again. When read this variable provides the value 0.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlAdminPassword.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlAdminPassword
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlAdminPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with administrator rights. It can only be changed by the administrator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigPassword.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigPassword
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSessCntrlConfigPassword.description: This password protects access to the variables with configurator rights. It can be changed by the administrator and by the configurator. If no password was assigned, the valid password is public. When read this variable provides a null-pointer.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartMode.description: Mode of the day of the week for which the change is made from winter time to summer time.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartWday.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartWday

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartMin.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartMin
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStartMin.description: Minute in which the time zone is changed from winter to summer time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMonth.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMonth
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMonth.description: Month in which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMode.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMode
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMode.description: Mode of the week day on which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopWday.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopWday
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopWday.description: Day of the week on which the change is made from summer time to winter time.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopHrs.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopHrs
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopHrs.description: Hour at which the time zone is changed from summer to winter time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMin.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMin
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStTzStopMin.description: Minute at which the time zone is changed from summer to winter time with respect to UTC.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPTimeServer1.description: IP address or name of the 1st time server in ASCII

wtWebioEA2x2ERPTsEnable.description: Binary coded conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Apply Time Server

wtWebioEA2x2ERPDnsServer2.description: IP address of the 2nd DNS server in ASCII

wtWebioEA2x2ERPAddConfig.description: Additional configuration (1=ON): Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1: DHCP enable Bit 0: BOOTP enable

wtWebioEA2x2ERPStartup.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPStartup
wtWebioEA2x2ERPStartup.description: Binary coded start page, more than one page must not be selected: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 2: user.htm Bit 1: home.htm Bit 0: index.htm

wtWebioEA2x2ERPGetHeaderEnable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPGetHeaderEnable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPGetHeaderEnable.description: If bits are set, every answer of a short form GET question will be lead by the IP-address and name of the device (Header) or a HTTP header (HTTP): Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 2-7: unused Bit 1 : GET HTTP enable Bit 0 : GET Header enable

wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpInputTrigger.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpInputTrigger
wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpInputTrigger.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-1: Digital inputs 0-1

wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpPort.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpPort
wtWebioEA2x2ERPHttpPort.description: Definition of the standard HTML port (Default: 80).

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailReply.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailReply

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailServer.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailServer
wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailServer.description: Name or IP address of the mail server.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailEnable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailEnable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailEnable.description: Set this bit to enable the sending of mails: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : Mail enable

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthentication.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthentication
wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthentication.description: Selection of the authentication modi: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : POP3 before SMTP Bit 1 : ESMTP, authentication Bit 0 : SMTP, no authentication

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthUser.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthUser
wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailAuthUser.description: Name of the user to be authenticated.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailPop3Server.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailPop3Server
wtWebioEA2x2ERPMailPop3Server.description: Name or Ip-address of the POP3 Servers.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpEnable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpEnable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpEnable.description: Set bit 0 to enable SNMP. If disabled, the device did not respond to any SNMP requests. Bit 1 decided wether the community string of read operations is compared with the system password or not: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : SNMP enable

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapManagerIP.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapManagerIP
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapManagerIP.description: Name or IP address of the TCP server which accepts the system trap.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapEnable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapEnable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPSnmpSystemTrapEnable.description: Binary coded trigger conditions: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 0: ColdStart Bit 1: WarmStart Bit 2: Diag messages Bit 3-7: unused

wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpAdminPort.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpAdminPort
wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpAdminPort.description: Udp port to which the Udp queries ( short form GET requests) can be sent. This port number must be unique within the device.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpEnable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpEnable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpEnable.description: Set this bit to enable UDP support: Octet 1: unused Octet 2: unused Octet 3: unused Octet 4: Bit 1-7: unused Bit 0 : UDP enable

wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpRemotePort.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpRemotePort
wtWebioEA2x2ERPUdpRemotePort.description: Udp remote port setting. If this value is set to zero, the source port read from a request will be used as destination port for the answer. A non zero value forced the destination port to this value.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTable.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTable
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTable.description: Table of properties of the binary mode.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryOperationMode.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryOperationMode
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryOperationMode.description: Selection of the operation mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 3-7: unused Bit 2 : UDP Peer Bit 1 : TCP Client Bit 0 : TCP Server

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpServerLocalPort.description: Local TCP port for data exchange in this server mode. This port number must be unique within the device. Reserved port number must not be used (refere to the manual).

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpServerInputTrigg.description: Every change on the inputs causes their state to be transmitted to the remote device. To minimize data traffic, individual inputs may be exempted from this rule. Nevertheless every transmission will contain all input bits. If a bit is set (1), a change of state on the corresponding input triggers a transmission. If the bit is not set (0), no transmission takes place. The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, with each bit corresponding to an input. Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4, Bit 0-1: Digital inputs 0-1

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpServerApplicatio.description: Selection of the application mode: The OCTETS are interpreted bit-by-bit, Bit 0 corresponds to the LSB. OCTET 1: unused OCTET 2: unused OCTET 3: unused OCTET 4: Bit 4-7: unused Bit 3 : OPC Device Bit 2 : Box2Box Slave Bit 1 : Compatible 50xxx Bit 0 : Default

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientLocalPort.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientLocalPort
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientLocalPort.description: Local TCP port for data exchange in this client mode. This port number must be unique within the device. Reserved port number must not be used (refere to the manual).

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPort.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPort
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPort.description: Port number of the server. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the server port to zero.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerIpAd.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerIpAddr
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerIpAd.description: Ip address of the server. A complete set of port number, IP address and a valid input/output mask starts this mode. No data exchange take place when setting the server IP address to 0.0.0.0.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPass.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPassword
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientServerPass.description: Building a connection may be protected by the administrator password of the server. Enter the server password to establish the connection, if a server administrator password exists.

wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientInactivity.name: wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientInactivity
wtWebioEA2x2ERPBinaryTcpClientInactivity.description: Connection timeout in 100ms. If no data are exchanged within the specified time, the device closes the connection to the server. The value 0 deactivates the timer. Using the Box2Box mode this function is disabled.
